      <div xml:id="NA247-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu “nīṭṭiyāmai varai” eṉat (ET: varaikeṉat) tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante comforted HER who had become weak in the time of separation.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA247">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            toṉṟupaṭu tuppoṭu muraṇmikac ciṉaiik</l>
<l>            koṉṟa yāṉaic ceṅkōṭu kaḻāa</l>
<l>            vaḻituḷip poḻinta viṉkura leḻili</l>
<l>            yeḵkuṟu pañciṟ ṟāki vaikaṟaik</l>
<l>            kōṭuyar neṭuvarai yāṭu nāṭanī </l>
<l>            nalkā yāyiṉu nayaṉila ceyyiṉu</l>
<l>            niṉvaḻip paṭūumeṉ ṟōḻi naṉuta</l>
<l>            liruntiṟai kūṭiya pacalaikku</l>
<l>            maruntupiṟi tiṉmainaṟ kaṟintaṉai ceṉmē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>O man from a land, where the sweet-voiced clouds,</l>
<l rend="indent2">from which the dwindling drops have flown</l>
<l rend="indent2">without washing<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kaḻāa</term>: T.V.G. takes the form as affirmative here.</note> the red horn of the elephant that killed,</l>
<l rend="indent3">in an uprise of long-established bitter<note place="foot">For a formulaic cognate line see NA 294.5, where the only deviation is <term xml:lang="ta">uṟai</term> for <term xml:lang="ta">paṭu</term>. Parallels such as KT 88.3 with <term xml:lang="ta">tol muraṇ</term> suggest that actually <term xml:lang="ta">tōṉṟu-paṭu</term> might rather be another attribute of <term xml:lang="ta">muraṇ</term> than of <term xml:lang="ta">tuppu</term>. <term xml:lang="ta">tuppoṭu muraṇ</term> then might be an antagonism followed up with vigour, that is, a bitter enmity. (There are, however, other parallels such as PN 213.5+14, where we find <term xml:lang="ta">toṉṟu-uṟai tuppiṉ</term>, "of a vigour lasting of old", and <term xml:lang="ta">niṉṟa tuppoṭu</term>, "with permanent vigour", so <term xml:lang="ta">toṉṟu-paṭu tuppoṭu muraṇ</term> might also be an enmity of lasting bitterness.)</note> antagonism,</l>
<l rend="indent">are playing on the long mountains on peak-height</l>
<l rend="indent4">at dawn, having become edged cotton<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">pañciṟṟū</term>: T.V.G. explains this form not as a n.sg., but as a suffix of comparison. This is, however, not necessary; we can as well understand a metaphor. Moreover we have to ask what <term xml:lang="ta">eḵku-uṟu</term> is supposed to mean. T.V.G. explains <term xml:lang="ta">eḵku</term> ("instrument") as a tool used for cleansing cotton (for which there would be a parallel in NA 299.7 with <term xml:lang="ta">vil</term>), but to me it seems to refer simply to the clear-cut outlines of the clouds.</note>,</l>
<l>– you have understood well that there is no other remedy</l>
<l rend="indent">for the pallor that came to [her] limbs, having been [first only]<note place="foot">Thus T.V.G.’s way to rationalise the <term xml:lang="ta">iruntu</term>: first the pallor stayed only on the forehead, then it spread. I, for my part, somehow do not believe in lines beginning with an absolutive (unless it is adverbial).</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">on the good forehead of my friend who follows your way,</l>
<l>even if you don’t grant [your presence],</l>
<l>even if you act unlongingly,</l>
<l rend="indent4">go!</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
